TY  - JOUR
JO  - Parallel and Distributed Systems, IEEE Transactions on
TI  - Self-Disciplinary Worms and Countermeasures: Modeling and Analysis
T2  - Parallel and Distributed Systems, IEEE Transactions on
IS  - 10
SN  - 1045-9219
VO  - 21
SP  - 1501
EP  - 1514
AU  - Wei Yu
AU  - Nan Zhang
AU  - Xinwen Fu
AU  - Wei Zhao
Y1  - Oct. 2010
PY  - 2010
KW  - Internet
KW  - game theory
KW  - invasive software
KW  - Internet
KW  - detection probability
KW  - game theoretic formulation
KW  - self-disciplinary worms
KW  - worm detection schemes
KW  - worm propagation
KW  - Computer crime
KW  - Computer networks
KW  - Computer science
KW  - Computer security
KW  - Computer worms
KW  - Distributed computing
KW  - Forensics
KW  - Game theory
KW  - Traffic control
KW  - Web and internet services
KW  - Worm
KW  - anomaly detection.
KW  - game theory
VL  - 21
JA  - Parallel and Distributed Systems, IEEE Transactions on
DO  - 10.1109/TPDS.2009.161
AB  - In this paper, we address issues related to the modeling, analysis, and countermeasures of worm attacks on the Internet. Most previous work assumed that a worm always propagates itself at the highest possible speed. Some newly developed worms (e.g., &#x201C;Atak&#x201D; worm) contradict this assumption by deliberately reducing the propagation speed in order to avoid detection. As such, we study a new class of worms, referred to as self-disciplinary worms. These worms adapt their propagation patterns in order to reduce the probability of detection, and eventually, to infect more computers. We demonstrate that existing worm detection schemes based on traffic volume and variance cannot effectively defend against these self-disciplinary worms. To develop proper countermeasures, we introduce a game-theoretic formulation to model the interaction between the worm propagator and the defender. We show that an effective integration of multiple countermeasure schemes (e.g., worm detection and forensics analysis) is critical for defending against self-disciplinary worms. We propose different integrated schemes for fighting different self-disciplinary worms, and evaluate their performance via real-world traffic data.
ER  - 

TY  - CONF
JO  - Software Engineering (ICSE), 2012 34th International Conference on
TI  - Characterizing logging practices in open-source software
T2  - Software Engineering (ICSE), 2012 34th International Conference on
IS  - 
SN  - 0270-5257
VO  - 
SP  - 102
EP  - 112
AU  - Ding Yuan
AU  - Soyeon Park
AU  - Yuanyuan Zhou
Y1  - 2-9 June 2012
PY  - 2012
KW  - program compilers
KW  - public domain software
KW  - software tools
KW  - system monitoring
KW  - checker
KW  - compiler designer
KW  - language designer
KW  - logging practice characterization
KW  - open-source software
KW  - problematic logging code
KW  - programming practice
KW  - software logging
KW  - tool developer
KW  - History
KW  - Open source software
KW  - Printing
KW  - Production
KW  - Programming
KW  - Servers
KW  - empirical study
KW  - failure diagnosis
KW  - log message
KW  - log quality
VL  - 
JA  - Software Engineering (ICSE), 2012 34th International Conference on
DO  - 10.1109/ICSE.2012.6227202
AB  - Software logging is a conventional programming practice. While its efficacy is often important for users and developers to understand what have happened in the production run, yet software logging is often done in an arbitrary manner. So far, there have been little study for understanding logging practices in real world software. This paper makes the first attempt (to the best of our knowledge) to provide a quantitative characteristic study of the current log messages within four pieces of large open-source software. First, we quantitatively show that software logging is pervasive. By examining developers' own modifications to the logging code in the revision history, we find that they often do not make the log messages right in their first attempts, and thus need to spend a significant amount of efforts to modify the log messages as after-thoughts. Our study further provides several interesting findings on where developers spend most of their efforts in modifying the log messages, which can give insights for programmers, tool developers, and language and compiler designers to improve the current logging practice. To demonstrate the benefit of our study, we built a simple checker based on one of our findings and effectively detected 138 pieces of new problematic logging code from studied software (24 of them are already confirmed and fixed by developers).
ER  - 

