TY  - CONF
JO  - Data Mining, 2007. ICDM 2007. Seventh IEEE International Conference on
TI  - Failure Prediction in IBM BlueGene/L Event Logs
T2  - Data Mining, 2007. ICDM 2007. Seventh IEEE International Conference on
IS  - 
SN  - 1550-4786
VO  - 
SP  - 583
EP  - 588
AU  - Liang, Y.
AU  - Zhang, Y.
AU  - Hui Xiong
AU  - Sahoo, R.
Y1  - 28-31 Oct. 2007
PY  - 2007
KW  - fault diagnosis
KW  - fault tolerant computing
KW  - parallel machines
KW  - pattern classification
KW  - support vector machines
KW  - IBM BlueGene/L event logs
KW  - RIPPER
KW  - failure prediction
KW  - fault-tolerant strategies
KW  - frequent failures
KW  - high-end computing
KW  - nearest neighbor method
KW  - rule-based classifier
KW  - support vector machines
KW  - Accuracy
KW  - Data mining
KW  - Fault tolerance
KW  - Nearest neighbor searches
KW  - Predictive models
KW  - Runtime
KW  - Supercomputers
KW  - Support vector machine classification
KW  - Support vector machines
KW  - System performance
VL  - 
JA  - Data Mining, 2007. ICDM 2007. Seventh IEEE International Conference on
DO  - 10.1109/ICDM.2007.46
AB  - Frequent failures are becoming a serious concern to the community of high-end computing, especially when the applications and the underlying systems rapidly grow in size and complexity. In order to develop effective fault-tolerant strategies, there is a critical need to predict failure events. To this end, we have collected detailed event logs from IBM BlueGene/L, which has 128 K processors, and is currently the fastest supercomputer in the world. In this study, we first show how the event records can be converted into a data set that is appropriate for running classification techniques. Then we apply classifiers on the data, including RIPPER (a rule-based classifier), Support Vector Machines (SVMs), a traditional Nearest Neighbor method, and a customized Nearest Neighbor method. We show that the customized nearest neighbor approach can outperform RIPPER and SVMs in terms of both coverage and precision. The results suggest that the customized nearest neighbor approach can be used to alleviate the impact of failures.
ER  - 

