JO  - Dependable Systems and Networks, 2005. DSN 2005. Proceedings. International Conference on
TI  - Filtering failure logs for a BlueGene/L prototype
T2  - Dependable Systems and Networks, 2005. DSN 2005. Proceedings. International Conference on
IS  - 
SN  - 
VO  - 
SP  - 476
EP  - 485
AU  - Liang, Y.
AU  - Zhang, Y.
AU  - Anand Sivasubramaniam
AU  - Sahoo, R.K.
AU  - Moreira, J.
AU  - Gupta, M.
Y1  - 28 June-1 July 2005
PY  - 2005
KW  - IBM computers
KW  - failure analysis
KW  - parallel machines
KW  - IBM BlueGene/L prototype
KW  - error event log filtering
KW  - failure log filtering
KW  - parallel machines
KW  - temporal filtering
KW  - three-step filtering algorithm
KW  - Application software
KW  - Condition monitoring
KW  - Error analysis
KW  - Filtering
KW  - Hardware
KW  - Large-scale systems
KW  - Military computing
KW  - Parallel machines
KW  - Prototypes
KW  - System software
VL  - 
JA  - Dependable Systems and Networks, 2005. DSN 2005. Proceedings. International Conference on
DO  - 10.1109/DSN.2005.50
AB  - The growing computational and storage needs of several scientific applications mandate the deployment of extreme-scale parallel machines, such as IBM's BlueGene/L, which can accommodate as many as 128K processors. In this paper, we present our experiences in collecting and filtering error event logs from a 8192 processor BlueGene/L prototype at IBM Rochester, which is currently ranked #8 in the Top-500 list. We analyze the logs collected from this machine over a period of 84 days starting from August 26, 2004. We perform a three-step filtering algorithm on these logs: extracting and categorizing failure events; temporal filtering to remove duplicate reports from the same location; and finally coalescing failure reports of the same error across different locations. Using this approach, we can substantially compress these logs, removing over 99.96% of the 828,387 original entries, and more accurately portray the failure occurrences on this system.
ER  - 

TY  - CONF
JO  - Dependable Computing, 1999. Proceedings. 1999 Pacific Rim International Symposium on
TI  - Networked Windows NT system field failure data analysis
T2  - Dependable Computing, 1999. Proceedings. 1999 Pacific Rim International Symposium on
IS  - 
SN  - 
VO  - 
SP  - 178
EP  - 185
AU  - Xu, J.
AU  - Kalbarczyk, Z.
AU  - Iyer, R.K.
Y1  - 1999
PY  - 1999
KW  - computer network management
KW  - fault tolerant computing
KW  - network operating systems
KW  - network servers
KW  - software management
KW  - software reliability
KW  - system recovery
KW  - NT System Logs
KW  - application software failures
KW  - error propagation
KW  - event logs
KW  - field failure data analysis
KW  - individual server failures
KW  - measurement-based dependability study
KW  - networked Windows NT system
KW  - system reboot information
KW  - system software
KW  - total system downtime
KW  - Buildings
KW  - Computer networks
KW  - Data analysis
KW  - File systems
KW  - Hardware
KW  - High performance computing
KW  - Network servers
KW  - Postal services
KW  - Production systems
KW  - Read only memory
VL  - 
JA  - Dependable Computing, 1999. Proceedings. 1999 Pacific Rim International Symposium on
DO  - 10.1109/PRDC.1999.816227
AB  - This paper presents a measurement-based dependability study of a Networked Windows NT system based on field data collected from NT System Logs from 503 servers running in a production environment over a four-month period. The event logs at hand contains only system reboot information. We study individual server failures and domain behavior in order to characterize failure behavior and explore error propagation between servers. The key observations from this study are: (1) system software and hardware failures are the two major contributors to the total system downtime (22% and 10%), (2) recovery from application software failures are usually quick, (3) in many cases, more than one reboots are required to recover from a failure, (4) the average availability of an individual server is over 99%, (5) there is a strong indication of error dependency or error propagation across the network, (6) most (58%) reboots are unclassified indicating the need for better logging techniques, (7) maintenance and configuration contribute to 24% of system downtime
ER  - 

